<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>“Potholes are a problem in the area, so our work is very important for motorists,” he said.“We fill up the potholes with sand and the motorists appreciate what we do. “Most of them give us a few rands for our work.Melusi told the People’s Paper he couldn’t study after matric because his family had no money.“Both my parents are unemployed, but they often get piece jobs to put food on the table,” said Melusi.“I decided to fill up potholes because I felt I should help my parents, as I am the eldest child in the family.” He said they started filling up potholes three years ago and the little money they get helps them survive.“We are able to buy food and clothes for ourselves. Some motorists are generous, others are stingy. “But we accept anything because we can’t force people to give us cash. It’s not their duty to pay us.”Philani said they were grateful to the generous drivers. “We are doing this job because we need money to survive.”